    riskFactors: ["Autosomal recessive inheritance (carrier frequency 1:90)", "Consanguinity increases risk", "Siblings of affected individuals (25% risk)", "Unexplained liver disease in children or young adults", "Unexplained neuropsychiatric symptoms in young adults"],
    diagnostics: ["Serum ceruloplasmin: < 20 mg/dL (low in 85-90% of Wilson disease patients)", "24-hour urine copper: > 100 mcg/day (> 40 mcg/day suspicious in children)", "Serum free (non-ceruloplasmin-bound) copper: elevated > 25 mcg/dL", "Slit-lamp examination: Kayser-Fleischer rings (copper deposits in Descemet membrane — present in 95% with neurological Wilson, 50% with hepatic)", "Hepatic copper content: > 250 mcg/g dry weight on liver biopsy (gold standard)", "ATP7B genetic testing (confirms diagnosis, enables family screening)", "MRI brain: T2 hyperintensity in basal ganglia, 'face of the giant panda' sign in midbrain", "LFTs, CBC, coagulation studies (assess hepatic function)"],
    management: ["Lifelong copper chelation therapy: D-penicillamine or trientine", "D-penicillamine 1-2 g/day in divided doses (first-line but more side effects)", "Trientine 750-1500 mg/day in divided doses (better tolerated, preferred by many)", "Zinc acetate 150 mg/day (blocks intestinal copper absorption — used as maintenance or adjunct)", "Dietary copper restriction: avoid liver, shellfish, chocolate, mushrooms, nuts", "Monitor 24-hour urine copper and free copper levels to assess treatment response", "Liver transplantation for fulminant hepatic failure or decompensated cirrhosis unresponsive to chelation", "Screen first-degree relatives with ceruloplasmin, urine copper, and genetic testing", "Pyridoxine 25 mg/day with D-penicillamine (prevents B6 deficiency)"],
