    cellular: { title: "UBE3A Gene Loss in the Brain", content: "Angelman syndrome (AS) results from loss of function of the maternally inherited UBE3A gene at chromosome 15q11.2-q13 — the same chromosomal region as Prader-Willi syndrome but involving the OPPOSITE parental allele (maternal vs paternal). UBE3A encodes a ubiquitin-protein ligase (E6-AP) involved in proteasome-mediated protein degradation. In neurons, UBE3A is exclusively expressed from the maternal allele (paternal allele is imprinted/silenced) — therefore, loss of the maternal copy eliminates all UBE3A expression in the brain. Mechanisms: (1) Maternal deletion of 15q11.2-q13 (70%), (2) UBE3A point mutation (11%), (3) Paternal uniparental disomy (7%), (4) Imprinting center defect (3%). UBE3A loss impairs synaptic plasticity, long-term potentiation, and dendritic spine morphology in cortical and hippocampal neurons. Prevalence: 1:12,000-20,000." },
